04908nam a22008055i 9781400837281DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2008    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008372817 a10.1515/97814008372812doi  a(DE-B1597)446941  a(OCoLC)979779869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aKrause, Sharon R., eauthor.10aCivil Passions :bMoral Sentiment and Democratic Deliberation /cSharon R. Krause.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. Citizenship, Judgment, and the Politics of Passion -- tCHAPTER ONE. Justice and Passion in Rawls and Habermas -- tCHAPTER TWO. Recent Alternatives to Rationalism -- tCHAPTER THREE. Moral Sentiment and the Politics of Judgment in Hume -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Affective Judgment in Democratic Politics -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Public Deliberation and the Feeling of Impartiality -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Affective Authority of Law -- tCONCLUSION. Toward a New Politics of Passion: Civil Passions and the Promise of Justice -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMust we put passions aside when we deliberate about justice? Can we do so? The dominant views of deliberation rightly emphasize the importance of impartiality as a cornerstone of fair decision making, but they wrongly assume that impartiality means being disengaged and passionless. In Civil Passions, Sharon Krause argues that moral and political deliberation must incorporate passions, even as she insists on the value of impartiality. Drawing on resources ranging from Hume's theory of moral sentiment to recent findings in neuroscience, Civil Passions breaks new ground by providing a systematic account of how passions can generate an impartial standpoint that yields binding and compelling conclusions in politics. Krause shows that the path to genuinely impartial justice in the public sphere--and ultimately to social change and political reform--runs through moral sentiment properly construed. This new account of affective but impartial judgment calls for a politics of liberal rights and democratic contestation, and it requires us to reconceive the meaning of public reason, the nature of sound deliberation, and the authority of law. By illuminating how impartiality feels, Civil Passions offers not only a truer account of how we deliberate about justice, but one that promises to engage citizens more effectively in acting for justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aFairness. 0aJustice. 0aPolitical psychology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Univ. Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311041343408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400837281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400837281.jpg  a978-3-11-041343-4  Princeton Univ. Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-045953-1  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  